host: arm-zen (Hetzner cax21, aarch64 Neoverse-N1, 4 cores, 7.5 GB RAM)
date: 2026-05-30
toolchain: cargo 1.96.0 (stable); RUSTFLAGS unset (runtime SIMD dispatch)

SCOPE NOTE: the zenjxl wrapper crate has NO benches of its own. All JXL encode
benches live in the SEPARATE jxl-encoder crate (its own git repo, a path-sibling
dependency of zenjxl). This file documents the ARM bench-unblock + profile of
that encode path, and the resulting honest finding for the zenjxl wrapper.

BENCH UNBLOCK (the baseline blocker):
  jxl-encoder/Cargo.toml [dependencies] declares two path deps into a
  zenmetrics workspace that is NOT present on the build box:
    cvvdp-gpu = { path = "../zenmetrics/crates/cvvdp-gpu" }            (non-optional)
    cvvdp-cpu = { package = "cvvdp", path = "../zenmetrics/crates/cvvdp",
                  optional = true }
  With those paths missing, cargo cannot even PARSE the manifest, so EVERY
  jxl-encoder bench failed ("failed to load manifest for dependency cvvdp:
  No such file or directory").
  FIX (box-only, NOT committed to jxl-encoder): created two minimal stub lib
  crates at the exact expected paths
  (zenmetrics/crates/cvvdp-gpu and zenmetrics/crates/cvvdp), each an empty
  `pub`-less lib with the right package name + version. jxl-encoder's library
  src/ has ZERO references to either crate's API (grep: 0 hits) — they are used
  only by examples/cvvdp_track_baseline.rs and the cvvdp_calibration bench
  (required-features = ["cvvdp-metric"]) — so empty stubs satisfy the manifest
  and let the library + the 5 self-contained benches build and run.
  `cargo metadata` -> OK after stubs.
  Benches now runnable (synthetic in-memory data, no corpus needed):
    predictor_prune_microbench, distance_sweep, epf_dispatch_ab,
    tree_learn_split_read_pattern, context_model_microbench.
  cvvdp_calibration is STILL not runnable (needs the real cvvdp metric crate).

BUILD: cargo build --release --bench predictor_prune_microbench -j2
  -> BUILD OK on 7.5 GB RAM, NO OOM (peak avail stayed >2 GB). ~12 min on 4 cores.
  NOTE: builds must run under a login shell (`bash -lc`) on this box — a bare
  tmux send-keys env lacks the toolchain PATH/cc setup and fails to link.

PROFILED: predictor_prune_microbench, group `prune_all_predictors`
  baseline: 156.41 ms median (range 155.84-157.05 ms, 100 samples)
  profiler: perf 6.8.12, record -g -F 999 --profile-time 15; report --no-children
  top self-time hotspot:
    74.40%  jxl_encoder::modular::predictor::PredictorAccumulator::predict_at
     8.13%  bench harness prune driver (predictor_prune_microbench)
     4.79%  memset / allocation (test-image setup)

HONEST FINDING / NO IN-TREE OPTIMIZATION FOR zenjxl:
  The dominant hotspot (predict_at, 74% self-time) lives ENTIRELY inside the
  external jxl-encoder crate (separate repo), NOT in the zenjxl wrapper. The
  zenjxl crate is a thin wrapper (jxl-encoder + zenjxl-decoder + PixelBuffer
  glue) with no YUV/predictor kernel of its own to optimize. predict_at
  re-matches the Predictor enum per pixel and gathers all neighbor samples even
  for predictors that need fewer — both are plausible jxl-encoder optimizations,
  but a change there alters encoder-core output and MUST be validated with a
  full encode-roundtrip byte-identity check (this synthetic microbench is not
  sufficient proof). Per task scope (modify zenjxl/zenavif only; treat any
  jxl-encoder change as a separate honest decision), NOT shipped to jxl-encoder.
  Documented here so a future jxl-encoder-scoped session can pick it up.
